description.narrative: Technical Support Team consists of experts providing expertise supporting quality implementation of the programme in various topicsand themes such as capacity strengthening, learning and innovation, civic space, conflict sensitivity, safeguarding, influencing, MEAL etc.

participating-org.narrative: Oxfam Novib was founded in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994. Oxfam Novib is member of the Oxfam International confederation. Working together in the confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education for all, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies. Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy. Oxfam Novib’s the Hague office contributes towards this project’s implementation.

comment.narrative: A Mutual Capacity Strengthening baseline survey was conducted in 2021, screening seven different capacities under the topic of influencing and awareness raising on SRHR for young people. These are: developing an influencing strategy; youth-led influencing; lobby and/or advocacy on policies and practices; public campaigning; digital campaigning; working with traditional media; and influencing social norms. The topics which emerged as the ones with the most indicated needs among partners engaged at regional and global level: developing an influencing strategy; lobby and/or advocacy on policies and practices; youth-led influencing; and digital campaigning. The topics where partners most often indicated an offer on capacity strengthening were influencing social norms and working with traditional media. (Organisations could express a need, an offer, or both a need and offer on the same topic.

Oxfam Novib will be familiar with the data lake dashboard and digital tools (such as social listening). Using data lake partner can collect, analyse and visualise data collected from their (digital) platform. The dashboard ensures that data can be analysed throughout countries, and how it actually can be used to advocate for safe and adequate SRHR information; while using digital tools partner will be able to be informed, monitor and evaluate online campaigns and use this data for better advocacy. RNW Media will have adopted additional digital tools, as well as improved using digital data for advocacy purposes.

IO 2.1 CSOs working with young people are empowered to form partnerships for collective advocacy on SRHR for diverse young people
KI-10b # Advocacy initiatives at all other levels (national/international) in which CSOs/movements undertake collective action towards SRHR for diverse young people

comment.narrative: Young people and marginalized groups face challenges with regard to meaningful participation in international political processes and events, such as HLPF and CSW. Data on specific digital communities providing and accessing online SRHR information is often collected on country level but a regional merge of information (that can be used for regional advocacy) is lacking. Regional partners are connected to different extents on a regional level with groups and activists. They have the ability to expand the networks but so far they lacked the resources online and offline to expand this network. One of the regional partners seeks to support young people with innovative means to advocate for their SRHR.. Oxfam Regional Platform through the Enough! campaign indirectly engages youth in generating initiatives on their SRHR as well as through supporting youth networks this will encourage generating initiatives/trainings in their respective countries.

Oxfam Novib will support at least two youth led coalitions to advocate for their SRHR (online and offline) at international structures/spaces such as HLPF and CSW. RNW Media will co-create several global campaigns towards SRHR that are mostly linked with international "days". For example, RNW Media will use country specific cases from the Masarouna programme to develop a global campaign to prevent censorship on social media. An example will be the collaborative effort of national partners and global partners with/by/for diverse young people during 16 days of activism and the Enough! campaign. Through the research of one of the regional partners, more networks, exchanges and learnings will be developed. The research on inequality and SRHR aims to open windows for collective influencing initiatives building on the evidence based data that the research will generate, while a second regional partner will be able to widen and increase both advocacy and influencing capacity at the regional level through the interventions and exchanges. A third regional partner aims at organising country-wide campaigns and festivals including film festival as well as organising regional campaigns using new media.

KI-11a # Cases at all other levels (national/international) where CSOs/movements succeed in creating space for their demands and positions

comment.narrative: International instruments such as UPRs (Universal Period Reviews), VNRs (Voluntary National Reviews/SDGs) and CEDAW reports are a key tool for accountability for the SDGs and Human Rights treaties, including on SRHR and Civic Space, both at the national and global level. They provide an important opportunity for CSOs to hold their governments and global leaders accountable, especially for members of civil society who have limited space to participate in accountability processes at a national level.

Oxfam Novib, in coordination with consortium partners, will support country teams & partners engaging in UPR, VNR and CEDAW processes to use these spaces to create space for their demands and positions. Oxfam Regional Platform will explore ways to support youth networks and hosting partners to gather youth from across the region to discuss and reflect on issues related to SRHR and come up with modes to deliver and advocate on those issues.

KI-1a # Governmental policies blocked, adopted and/or improved to enable diverse young people to enjoy their SRHR

comment.narrative: The Dutch government has a leadership role on SRHR funding in the world. However, the current Grant Instrument SRHR Partnership Fund, Policy Framework for Strengthening Civil Society of the Dutch government is ending in 2025. Southern based CSOs, in particular WROs, depend on access to this type of funding to do their work.

We are lobbying towards the Dutch Government , through Wo=Men and the SRHR lobby group for the Netherlands to keep (and preferably expand) their leadership role in the world on SRHR and for funding to stay available (specifically for Southern based CSOs)to promote and work on gender equality and social inclusion within their own contexts.

comment.narrative: In total, 6 organizations are involved in the programme in 2021 at regional/global level: 4 at regional level, and 2 at global level. From 2022, a 7th organisation (regional level) shall also be engaged. Three women led organisations are involved at the time of the baseline: Oxfam Regional Platform and two regional partners. Oxfam Regional Platform will play an important role in strengthening the regional component of Masarouna through regional campaigning and linking and learning from the interventions in the MENA countries. One regional partner has accumulated experience in dissemination of SRHR education and became a reference for many initiatives in the region. The other regional partner has developed through their work in research and capacity building workstreams relevant to SRHR; an experience that enables them to address basic needs of sister organizations especially those working with vulnerable communities.

On regional and global level, consortium members strive for equal partnership. In decision making structure, consortium partners strive for co-creation and inclusive decision making. Consortium partners acknowledge that decision making processes can therefore take longer but it is imperative to ensure meaningful involvement of all partners. Collaboration between Oxfam Regional Platform and Oxfam Novib is taking shape, with joint activities in linking and learning and campaigning through the Enough! campaign. Oxfam Regional Platform has built partnerships with regional partners, agreed on mutual expectations and will be working towards enhancing and shaping their partnership relations.

The partnership will be strengthened as the consortium partners get to know each other and each other's strengths better, which will enable a further increase in Southern leadership and strengthening of feminist ways of working. We would see the partnership evolve through collaboration, joint learning meetings, regular exchanges and possible introduction of new partners, which can be identified through the implementation and assessment of project activities

Oxfam Novib will work with Oxfam Regiional Platform, especially around changing social norms on SRHR for young people, regional campaigns and linking and learning. RNW Media aims to further explore new ways to promote learning and exchanging expertise with Oxfam Regional Platform and look for effective ways for partnership building, meeting structures and effective decision making. Oxfam Regional Platform would like to see the partnership with regional partners evolve in 2022 through collaboration, joint learning meetings, regular exchanges and possible introduction of new partners, which can be identified through the implementation and assessment of project activities.

description.narrative: KI-16 # CSOs/movements, not women or youth led, engaged in Masarouna

comment.narrative: In total, 6 organizations are involved in the programme in 2021 at regional/global level: 4 at regional level, and 2 at global level. From 2022, a 7th organisation (regional level) shall also be engaged. Two organisations that are not women or youth led are involved at the time of the baseline: consortium partners RNW Media and Oxfam Novib. Building on our combined experience in the region, the consortium - in 2021 comprising of the Arab Foundation for Freedoms and Equality (AFE), RNW Media and OxfamNovib - is uniquely positioned to advance the fulfilment of SRHR for our target group of diverse young people. The consortium was build on common views and values. The partners’ experience, existing networks and long-term relationships in MENA legitimizethe consortium’s ability to challenge social norms, stimulate discussion and strengthen civil society for increased government accountability. The consortium presents a cohesive and comprehensive response to SRHR programming needs in MENA. Oxfam Novib’sexperience in strengthening the influencing capacities of SRHR-focused partners, managing large grants, innovative sub-granting and learning mechanisms – paired with AFE’s capacity-building programme – present many opportunities to tap previously unexploredcollaboration possibilities. Complemented by RNW Media’s expertise in strengthening digital interventions and co-creating digital communities for social change, the consortium brings together different strong elements of each consortium member’s work thatadd value and maximize Masarouna’s potential for impact.

On regional and global level, consortium members strive for equal partnership. In decision making structure, consortium partners strive for co-creation and inclusive decision making. Consortium partners acknowledge that decision making processes can therefore take longer but it is imperative to ensure meaningful involvement of all partners. The partnership between RNW Media and Oxfam Novib has been strengthened over the first year of the project, leading to joint activities and capacity strengthening ofeach other's partners.

The partnership will be strengthened as the consortium partners get to know each other and each other's strengths better, which will enable a further increase in Southern leadership and strengthening of feminist ways of working. We would see the partnership evolve through collaboration, joint learning meetings, regular exchanges and possible introduction of new partners, which can be identified through the implementation and assessment of project activities.

RNW Media and Oxfam Novib will increase cooperation in influencing and advocacy activities, capacity strengthening (including of each other's partners) and work together on learning in the programme. RNW Media aims to further explore new ways to promotelearning and exchanging expertise with Oxfam Novib and look for effective ways for partnership building, meeting structures and effective decision making.

description.narrative: KI-16 # CSOs/movements, both women and youth led, engaged in Masarouna

comment.narrative:
In total, 6 organizations are involved in the programme in 2021 at regional/global level: 4 at regional level, and 2 at global level. From 2022, a 7th organisation (regional level) shall also be engaged.
One organisation that is both women and youthled is involved at the time of the baseline: consortium partner Arab Foundation for Freedoms and Equality (AFE). In 2022, a third regional partner that is both women and youth led will be engaged.
The third regional partner has collaborated in organizing a series of feminist circles which addressed several key issues as perceived and analysed by a diverse group of intersectional feminists who are either activists or scholars. The purpose was to create a safe space for in-depth feminist conversationsamongst activists who are the knowers and that would feed into policy dialogues and communication briefs as well as provide homegrown feminist knowledge that will inform and strengthen on-going feminist praxis in the MENA region.

On regional and global level, consortium members strive for equal partnership. In decision making structure, consortium partners strive for co-creation and inclusive decision making. Consortium partners acknowledge that decision making processes can therefore take longer but it is imperative to ensure meaningful involvement of all partners. Oxfam Novib has supported AFE in their organisational development and governance restructuring to become a more stable and transparent organisation.

The partnership will be strengthened as the consortium partners get to know each other and each other's strengths better, which will enable a further increase in Southern leadership and strengthening of feminist ways of working. We would see the partnership evolve through collaboration, joint learning meetings, regular exchanges and possible introduction of new partners, which can be identified through the implementation and assessment of project activities

In 2022, Oxfam Regional Platform will work with a third regional partner in amplifying the skills, engagement and role of diverse young people in promoting awareness, homegrown knowledge production, best practice, culture shift and positive public policies on SRHR; facilitating cross-regional linkages and collaboration amongst diverse young people in campaigning and lobbying for SRHR; engage diverse young people in MENA in global lobbying and advocacy on SRHR as well as facilitating their access to key global spaces such as the CSW, HLPF, and others and support and sustain the new generation of diverse MENA feminist youth activists in creating spaces for joint, sustainable, and powerful advocacy on SRHR.

description.narrative: KI-16 # Youth led CSOs/movements engaged in Masarouna
KI-17 # CSOs/movements, not women or youth led, engaged in Masarouna that have enhanced representation of constituencies

comment.narrative: The consortium will closely work together to develop a regional youth engagement strategy. In the Mutual Capacity Strengthening baseline survey conducted in 2021, most organisations expressed an offer for capacity strengthening on perception by and relationship with constituency, which indicates that most organisations have a strong capacity on this topic. An equal number of organisations expressed a need or an offer on youth engagement practices, which provides opportunities for mutual capacity strengthening.

As a result of close collaboration and co-creation sessions, Oxfam Novib and RNW Media have defined a regional youth engagement strategy by the end of 2022 and will have a position on how youth' representation can be enhanced and monitored in our programmes. The youth engagement strategy will consist of offline and online engagement components, with the participation of countries/national youth advisory committees and/or the main youth actors identified through the youth mapping exercise. The strategy will include a division of roles and responsibilities of youth participants in the rolling out of the strategy including youth identified indicators on how participants identify both their role and the change they want to achieve.
